**Distinct Distances in Higher Dimensions**

This is the natural generalization of the famous distinct distances problem (Erdős #89, solved by Guth-Katz 2015) to higher dimensions. Erdős posed this in 1946, proving that f_d(n) is between n^{1/d} and n^{2/d}.

**Key Contributors:**
- **Erdős (1946):** Original bounds n^{1/d} ≪ f_d(n) ≪ n^{2/d}
- **CEGSW (1990):** f_3(n) ≫ n^{1/2}
- **APST (2004):** f_d(n) ≫ n^{1/(d-90/77)-o(1)}
- **Solymosi-Vu (2008):** f_d(n) ≫ n^{2/d - c/d²} for d ≥ 4
- **Guth-Katz (2015):** Solved the 2D case
